{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491241"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:39:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:39:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"888"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/888"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.78,0.12,0.03,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"888"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108054"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/888"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"888"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90467"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"349"},{"type":"tags","id":"1240"},{"type":"tags","id":"2310"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1171"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13716"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37296"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108054"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of creamy white vaginal discharge associated with vulval and vaginal itch and irritation. This is the first time she has had these symptoms. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She is sexually active with a male partner who is asymptomatic. She is not pregnant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The vulva is oedematous and inflamed in appearance, and there is a thick white \u0022cottage cheese\u0022 discharge visible.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No treatment","Single dose oral fluconazole","Single dose metronidazole","Single dose ceftriaxone","Seven-day course of doxycycline"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic symptoms and signs of vulvovaginal candidiasis. White \u0022curd-like\u0022 or \u0022cottage cheese\u0022 discharge combined with vaginal itch is characteristic of an overgrowth of candida species. \u003Cem\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/em\u003E is a common vaginal commensal and \u003Cstrong\u003Eno treatment\u003C/strong\u003E is necessary if patients are asymptomatic. However, this patient is symptomatic and requires treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esingle dose of oral fluconazole\u003C/strong\u003E is an appropriate first-line treatment for uncomplicated vulvovaginal candidiasis. Oral therapy with fluconazole is as effective as intravaginal imidazole therapy. While intravaginal therapy may provide quicker symptomatic relief, oral therapy is generally preferred by patients due to its convenience.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle dose metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat trichomoniasis, not candidiasis. The symptoms and signs in this case are not consistent with these conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle dose ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used in the treatment of gonorrhoea. There is no indication of a sexually transmitted infection in this case, and the symptoms are not consistent with gonorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eseven-day course of doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is commonly used to treat chlamydia infections. Again, there is no indication of a sexually transmitted infection here, and the presentation is not consistent with chlamydia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while diagnosis can be confirmed by microscopy and culture, empiric treatment based on typical symptoms and signs is often appropriate in primary care. Confirmation by microscopy and culture can assist with differentiation of alternate diagnoses such as trichomonas or bacterial vaginosis that would require alternative treatments. Patients should be advised to avoid soaps and lubricants which may contribute to irritation. If symptoms persist or recur frequently, further investigation may be necessary to rule out other conditions such as diabetes or HIV, or to identify less common Candida species that may require different treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A single dose of oral fluconazole is effective treatment for acute candidal vulvovaginitis."],"references":["Candidiasis. Australian STI Management Guidelines. http://www.sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/infections-associated-with-sex/candidiasis#special-treatment-situations. Accessed 26/01/2021","Mizgier M, Jarzabek-Bielecka G, Mruczyk K, Kedzia W. The role of diet and probiotics in prevention and treatment of bacterial vaginosis and vulvovaginal candidiasis in adolescent girls and non-pregnant women. Ginekol Pol. 2020;91(7):412-416. doi: 10.5603/GP.2020.0070. PMID: 32779162. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32779162/","TG Complete [Internet]. West Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd; 2021. Assessment of candidal vulvovaginitis in adult females; [updated 2020 Dec; cited 2023 March 30]; [about 2 screens]. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Antibiotic\u0026topicfile=bartonella-infections\u0026guidelinename=auto\u0026sectionId=c_ABG_Candidal-vulvovaginitis-in-adult-females_topic_3#c_ABG_Candidal-vulvovaginitis-in-adult-females_topic_3"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90467"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"888"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90467"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-06T02:30:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-06T02:31:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"888"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108054"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdA